{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600659/1930071301/0670.xml":{"full_text":"News of Markets\nPages 1 to 4\nPart 6\u201412 Paget\nLOCAL BANK CALL\nSHOWS 55,1,005\nGAIN IN DEPOSITS\nOfficial Tabulation Reveals\nIncrease in All Three Groups\nSince March.\nNATIONAL BANKS ADDED\nMOST FUNDS TO BOOKS\nInformation for Controller Pole In-;\ndicates Greater Efforts Here\nToward Thrift.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nAn official tabulation showing the\ncondition of all the banks in Washing\nton on June 30. 1930, the date of Con\ntroller Pole\u2019s recent call, reveals that\ntotal deposits were $5,180,005.95 larger\nthan on the March 27 call.\nAccording to Audley A. P. Savage,\nauditor of the National Savings St Trust\nCo., deposits on June 30 were $262,-\n050.92688, in comparison with $256,-\n870,920.93 on March 27, proving the\nabove increase of more than $5,000,000.\nComparison with deposits a year ago\non the same date is also interesting.\nTotal deposits in local banks on June\n30, 1929. were $264,479,938.05, or only\n$2,429,011.17 more than they are now,\nin spite of the present unsatisfactory\nbusiness conditions and the low stock\nmarket.\nA comparison In deposits on March\n27, 1929, and March 27, 1930, or three\nmonths ago, reveals a decrease on March\n27, 1930, of $11,329,356.93. However,\na comparison of deposits on March 27,\n1929, and the call of June 30, this\nyear, shows a decrease of but $6,149,-\n350.98 Thus it is important to note\nthat while the other comparisons show\ndecreases, the figures called for a few\ndays ago by the controller show a\npick-up since March 27 which is highly\nsatisfactory.\nAll Groups Show Gains.\nAll three groups, national banks, sav\nings banks and trust companies, made\ngains over the call of three months\nago. The national banks made the best\nadvance. The figures show that the\nnational banks as a group added $3.-\n328,988.21 in deposits. The figures in\nthis list were given a particularly good\nboost by Riggs National and the Na\ntional Metropolitan.\nThe trust companies came second in\nlifting their deposits between calls. As\na group they reported an increase of\n$997,534.39. Os the trust companies,\nAmerican Security was the most suc\ncessful in raising the deposit total.\nThe savings banks were not far be\nhind the trust companies. The city's\nsavings institutions reported an increase\nin deposits of $855,483.35 since March.\nIn this group the Park Savings Bank,\nSecurity Savings St Cbmmercial, Bank\nof Commerce Savings and the Wash\nington Mechanics made especially good\nrecords.\nIt is an interesting fact that deposits\nIn the banks always increase in times\nof business depression. Less money is\nwanted for business purposes, less\nmoney is being spent, the public feels\nthe need of greater thrift and the\nmoney piles up in the banks. This is\nassigned by local bankers as the chief\nreason for the increase at this time.\nElsewhere in The Star\u2019s financial\nsection is printed Mr. Savage's complete\ntabulation of,the banking situation here\nso far as deposits are concerned. It\nis an interesting financial picture well\nworth looking at carefully.\nYield*May Check Bears.\n\u201cWe are inclined to the view,\u201d says\nthe United Business Service, \u201cthat the\nsituation in business, deplorable as it\nis, hardly warrants so pessimistic an\nattitude as is reflected in the recent\nliquidating movement.\n\"A 50-to-60 point decline from the\naverage level of stock prices in late\nMay seems no more warranted than did\nthe 45-to-50 point advance, which was\nstaged in the opening quarter. Just\na sit appeared early in April that things\nwere being overdone on the upside, so it\nappears now that poor conditions are\nbeing overemphasized on the down\nside.\n\"However, with quotations for many\nof the highest caliber issues now down\nto levels where income return furnishes\nincentive to buy for investment account,\nsuch stocks are less likely to be the\nobject of further bear attack.\u201d\nLonsdale Virginia Schoolboy.\nMany people will be surprised to know\nthat John G. Lonsdale, president of\nthe American Bankers\u2019 Association,\nwent to school in Virginia. In his re\ncent speech before the Virginia Bank\ners\u2019 Association, at Hot Springs, the\nnoted financier said:\n\u201cIt affords me immense pleasure to\nbe part of this splendid assemblage\nof Virginia bankers gathered here today\nto discuss the perplexing things to\nwhich the banking world has fallen\nheir. Virginia, the mother of States,\u2019\nalways has possessed a fascination for\nme. I love its rugged and picturesque\nmountains, its forest-clad slopes, its\nbeautiful. valleys and winding rivers,\nand above all its generous-hearted\npeople. It was not by chance that a\npart of my early education was obtained\nat the Episcopal High School near\nAlexandria, under the watchful care\nof such sterling gentlemen as Mr.\nBlackford and Col. Hoxton. A visit\nto Virginia, therefore, brings me among\nfriends and homefolk.\u201d\nWomen Control Vast Wealth.\nThe tendency of men to provide sub\nstantial estates in the form of life in\nsurance or other property for their\nwives in case, they are separated by\ndeath, places vast wealth under the\ncontrol of women at the present time.\nAccording to the Federation of Wom\nen\u2019s Advertising Clubs of the World,\nmore than 51 per cent of the million\naires of the United States are women,\nwhich is startling to those who have\nvisualized the typical millionaire as a\ncrabbed old gentleman with gout and a\nsour disposition.\nStatistics show that 70 per cent of\nthe estates left by men are left to\nwomen, and that women leave their\nestates to other women in 64 per cent\nof the cases noted. One reason for this\npreponderance to women is that men\nprovide for wives and daughters by\nleaving them estates, while they safe\nguard sons by starting them in business.\nInsurance Gains by Leaps.\nA life insurance company which re\nquired 40 years to rell up its first\nbillion dollars of insurance in force\nhas increased its business by an addi\ntional billion three times within the\npast five years. The mast recent net\nincrease of a billion required little\nmore than a year and a half of time.\nThe total insurance in force with the\nr organization now is mors than $7,000,-\n000,000 in face value.\nOff to Maine\nWILLIAM J. FLATHER,\nOne of the vice presidents of the Riggs\nNational Bank, who leaves here to\nmorrow for the Poland Spring House,\none of the best known resort hotels in\nthe Pine Tree State. The Washington\nbanker has spent his vacations there\nfor many years.\nTRADE STABILIZING\nFORMULA EVOLVED\n\u201cMathematical Approach to\nProsperity\u201d Spots Weak\nness in Output.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCAMBRIDGE. Mass., July 12.\u2014A for\nmula to stabilize business, character\nized as a \u201cmathematical approach to\nprosperity.\u201d has been developed at the\nMassachusetts Institute of Technology.\nIt may be employed to establish the\nproper balance between factory output\nand the ability of the country at large\nto absorb that output\u2014in short, it is\nintended to spot weaknesses in mass\nproduction generally.\nIt aims to make possible the reduc\ntion of stocks of merchandise and thus\nto make large amounts of capital avail\nable for reinvestment.\nThe formula, evolved by P. E. Ray\nmond. assistant professor of industrial\nresearch, is a set of equations which,\nhe believes, may be applied to the maze\nof costs involved in a $100,000,000 busi\nness or a SSOO business with equal ef\nfectiveness.\nStudy of Manufacturing.\nMr. Raymond worked out his formula\nfrom a study of manufacturing pro\ncesses, cost sheets and production\nrecords.\n\u201cThe figures analyzed,\u201d he said, \u201care,\nin general, the cost of material, labor\nand overhead, cost of capital invested\nin manufacturing operations, as well as\ninventories, rental and space charges,\nand certain losses from obsolescence\nand deterioration\u2014all of which must\nbear a definite relation to price if any\nindustrial activity is to be profitably\nconducted.\nHe finds that invested capital in\nmany cases may be reduced without\naffecting earning power.\nSavings may be effected, he says, by\nreduction in the quantity of goods\ncarried in inventories to meet current\nsales demand, whereupon the rate of\ncapital turnover may be increased\nproportionately.\nEmploying Working Capital.\nSavings also may be made. Mr.\nRaymond asserts, by employing working\ncapital to better advantage elsewhere\nin the business. Some capital may go\ntoward purchase of more highly de\nveloped machinery and thereby increase\nproductive capacity of each operator.\nIn some instances, he says, it is\nuneconomical to operate processes con\ntinuously under conditions of mass\nproduction when the consumption of\nthe finished product varied widely from\none period to another.\nThe proper balancing, he contends,\nmay achieve surprising economies.\n\"It is encouraging to note,\u201d Mr. Ray\nmond says, \u201cthe interest with which\nprogressive corporations already have\nadopted some form of scientific methods\nto control their policies. Scientific\nstudy of production is not new to them.\nTheir books already are in shape for\nthis type of mathematical analysis.\u201d\ntwo nevTdirectors\nON TRUST BOARD\nStandard Collateral Corporation\nElects C. C. Morgan and\nR. C. Jones.\nCharles Carroll Morgan and Robert\nC. Jones, co-managers of the Washing\nton offices of G. M. P. Murphy Co.,\nmembers of the New York Stock Ex\nchange, were elected to the board of\ndirectors Standard Collateral Shares\nCorporation, according to announcement\nmade by Maj. Gen. Kenzie W. Walker,\nelected president at the same meeting,\nsucceeding Robert O. Deyer, deceased.\nThe other directors of the corpora\ntion are Col. W. H. Clopton, Paul L.\nJames, Washington; Herbert S. Brady,\nassistant controller Union Pacific Rail\nway, New York City; W. T. Fredeking,\ndirector First National Bank, Hinton,\nW. Va., and George A. Randolph, Wash\nington.\nThe Standard Collateral Shares Cor\nporation is a local investment trust\ncompany of the semi-fixed type with\noffices in the Woodward Building and\nhas over 250 shareholders.\nFARM PURCHASING POWER\nONLY SLIGHTLY REDUCED\nAlthough the farmers\u2019 income will be\nreduced about 15 per cent this year, his\npurchasing power during the crop year\n1930-31 will be around 10 per cent be\nlow levels a year ago, says the Brook\nmire Economic Service. Prices of the\nthings the farmer has to buy have de\nclined in moderate degree, and this\ndecline will offset the loss in income\npartially.\nAnother point that is often lost sight\nof is that the major portions of most\ncrops are marketed between August and\nDecember. In those months of the\n1929-30 crop year prices were at the\nhighest level of the season.\nGROSS SALES GAIN.\nNational Shirt Shops, Inc., for the\nsix months ended June 30, 1930, reports\ngross sales of $2,014,606, against $1,829,-\n259 for the same perioA last year, an\nincrease of 10.13 per oedU\nFINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\n\u00a9ljc pundmi Star\nBROADER DEMAND\nFOR SENIOR ISSUES\nHELD GOOD OMEN\nBonds, Preferred Stocks and\nReal Estate Mortgages\nDraw More Attention.\nEASY MONEY SPEEDING\nRECOVERY IN BUSINESS\nHigh Average Yield on Stocks Are\nExpected to Act as Spur\nto Buying.\nt\nBY CHARLES F. SPEARE.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, July 12.\u2014With the\nbusiness situation still going through\nthe cure for overproduction and with\nspeculative securities unable to shake\noff the effects of Inflation and a year\nof false measurements of values, it is\nnatural that more consideration should\nbe given to corporation bonds, prefer\nred stocks and real estate mortgages,\nin which the quality of price stability\nj appeals to the investor, harried for\nmonths by the unsatisfactory perform\nance of his \u201cequity\u201d holdings.\nIn a week, therefore, that has devel\noped further unsettlement in stocks,\nwith prominent issues dropping to new\n\u201clows\u201d and others to the borderline,\nand that has witnessed depressed mar\nkets for commodities, it is satisfactory\nto note a broadening of demand for\nfixed interest obligations and an em\nphasis placed in public announcements\non the advantage in accumulating them\nat the current price level.\nFunds Going Into Bonds.\nIf easy money is the leaven by which\nindustry is to be restored to its normal\nj condition, it must work, in part,\nthrough the market for securities. First\nof all, however, this market has to be\ncleared of its surplus supplies to permit\nnew financing, out of which industrial\nexpansion may be presumed to develop.\nAs there Is such a spread between call\nand time money rates, bankers\u2019 bills,\nrates of deposit in New York banks\nand the return on high-grade rail\nroad and public utility bonds and on\nthe best of the foreign dollar issues,\nto say nothing of the net yield on\ntax-exempt securities, this difference in\nearning power will sooner or later force\nidle funds Into the bond market.\nAs a matter of fact, the bond mar\nket's improvement on Friday to the\nbest level of the year to date was evi\ndence that this move is actually under\nway. The week\u2019s figures of increased\nbank investments was further testi\nmony.\nIt is not improbable that during\nanticipated period of extremely low\nmoney rates in the next 60 days, defi\nnite signs of business recovery will ap\npear. coincident with a claser approach\nto satisfactory Investment market con\nditions than has been attained since the\nSpring of 1928.\nCommodities Affect Stocks.\nCommodity prices struck a new low\nlevel this week, wheat broke again in\nspite of unfavorable crop news and cot\nton reflected the July figures of pro\nduction and acreage. Conditions In this\nrespect are no different than in other\nparts of the world, except that there\nseems to be a more intimate relation\nin this country between market fluctua\ntions in commodities and securities\nthan elsewhere. The two groups go up\nand down together. An early divorce\nwould be helpful to the speculative stock\nmarket situation.\nAttention is again called to the high\naverage yields on stocks compared no\nonly with the low rates for money, but\nwith the average income obtaining in\nother periods of depression. This\neventually will lead to the same class\nof buying of assured dividend-paying\nshares as is now taking place in bonds\nand preferred stocks. It is significant\nthat among the shares that have had\nthe flabbiest appearance this week are\nthose on which the return is small,\nnotably the public utilities and certain\nof the overexploited industrials.\nPublic Attitude Changes.\nThe public obviously is getting back\nto a point of view that it held prior\nto 1928, and then abandoned for the\nfetish of capital appreciation as against\nincome return. What this leads to is\nillustarted in the case of such a for\nmerly popular stock as Simmons Co.,\nwhich in 1929 sold about 45 times\nearnings for that year, but has just\npassed its dividend and dropped to a\na point 90 per cent'under its high.\nObviously, the tendency to bear values\nI is today as strong as it was to boast\nthem 12 months ago. Prices in many\ninstances have come below the level\nof justification, taking into account the\nfactors of smaller earnings and reduced\ndividends.\nThere are now quite a few situations\nwhere the market price of a corpora\ntion stock is no higher than its paid\nin capital. When such conditions de\nvelop and values aggregating $8,000,-\n000,000 to $9,000,000,000 are taken from\nthe stocks of American industrials,\nrailroads, public utilities, banks, insur\nance companies and investment trusts\nt in less than two months, one may with\ns reasonable safety buy good \u201cequities\u201d\nt and look back on the Summer of 1930,\nas a time of exceptional investment\nopportunity.\n\"Frozen\u201d Investments Vital.\nMore important is the \u201cfrozen\u201d char\nacter of investments in individual com\npanies, where control of management\nhas been attempted and where the own\nership is reperesented in blocks of 100,-\nI 000 to 200,000 or more shares, on which\nonly nominal prices may be quoted.\nAny attempt to liquidate such invest\nt ments might easily result In a depre\nj elation of 25 to 50 per cent from the\nj last price.\n\u201cLiquidating values,\u201d as applied to\nthe stock of an investment \u201ctrust\u201d is,\ntherefore, not the yardstick to be used\nexclusively In measuring the reason\nableness of Its current price. There\nshould be some relation to income re\nturn which, while on the debentures\ne and preferred shares of the \u201ctrusts\u201d is\ns high, on junior issues it has been so\nr low as to prejudice investors against\nthem.\nThe practice of paying dividends in\ne stock has been overdone. This is to\nthe advantage of the corporation which\ns feels the need of a steady increase in\ne capital for purposes of expansion, but\nit has little In its favor for the stock\nt holder, especially in a declining market.\n(Copyright. 1930.)\n\ne BUSINESS NORMAL.\nNotwithstanding general business con\ntions, the W. F. Hall Printing Co. of\nChicago, the largest plant in the world\non one floor, is experiencing a normal\ne volume of business and profits are con\ns sidered satisfactory, Frpnk R. Warren,\npresident of the organization, recently\na told his board of directors at a special\nmartin*\n\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, JULY 13, 1930.\nSMALL LOAN DEALER EXPLAINS\nWHY RATES ARE OFTEN SO HIGH\nBusiness Man Notes Wide Difference in\nMethods \u2014Claims New Law Is\nINeedecl m District.\nBY I. A. FLEMING.\nA business man, evidently familiar\nwith the small loan business, has taken\nthe troub\u2019e to crit-\nI. A. Firming.\ndress of the writer are withheld slm\ni ply because permission to use them\nhas not be requested.\n\u201cWe have had brought to our atten\ntion your column \u201cBusiness News in\nRetrospect\u201d of May 25. in which you\ninclude some paragraphs concerning\nthe small loan business.\n\u201cWe judge from your treatment of\nthis issue that you have confused the\nvarious agencies making loans to indi\nviduals, as well as the legislation under\nwhich each operates.\nDifferent Types of Loans.\n\"In the first place, you make a tie\nup between the pawnbroker and the\nsmall loan dealer. The two are quite\ndifferent, operate under different sets\nof laws and deal with different types of\nindividuals. The pawnbroker, dealing\nusually with people who prefer not to\nhave their affairs known, can carry on\nhis business so much under cover as to\nenable him to charge unreasonable\nrates. This evil, however, is rapidly be\ning overcome through controlling legis\nlation, such as you have in Washing\nton.\n\"You next talk of unsecured small\nloans, saying that they may easily be\nobtained at banks and elsewhere. Then\nyou go on to say that SSOO may be bor\nrowed on good reputation by paying\nthe high charges resulting from a rate\nof 6 per cent discounted in full in\nadvance on a loan which must be paid\nback in installments, plus a $lO fee for\ninvestigation, plus something further\nfor insuring the loan, making advance\ncharges of about $45 on a SSOO loan.\n\"Assuming that the principal is paid\nup in the course of a year, the $45\ncharge on a SSOO loan would really be,\nas you see, $45 on an average of $250\nin the customer's hands, and that\nwould amount to about 18 per cent per\nannum. While 18 per cent sounds like\nan exorbitant rate, careful and unbiased\ninvestigations of the lending business\nhave shown that It is not possible to\nmake small loans to Individuals at rates\nmuch lower than that and still secure\na profit sufficient to attract capital to\nthe business. Unless lenders can show\ntheir stockholders as good returns as\ncan dealers in other necessities of life,\nthey will have no money to lend. Un-\nbiased statistical analyses have indicated j\nthat in order to compete with grocers,\nfurniture dealers, etc., from the stand-\nBUSINESS GAINS\n18 PCI. IN WEEK\nCommerce Department Bases\nFindings on Volume of\nChecks Presented.\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe Department of Commerce re\nports an increase of 18 per cent in busi\nness during the week ended July 5. as\ncompared with the previous week, bas\ning its findings on volume of checks\npresented for payment.\nWholesale prices, as a whole, re\nmained at the same level as a week\nago. but showed a decrease of 13 per\n1 cent when compared with the week\nended July 6. 1929. The average price\nof wheat at Kansas City declined\nslightly from the preceding week and\nwas lower than last year. Iron and\nsteel prices, as measured by the com\nposite index, although showing no\nchange from the w r eek ended June 28,\nwere 9 per cent lower than the same\nperiod in 1929.\nBank loans and discounts show'''\u2019 r> j\nslight decline from last week, but were\ngreater than the corresponding weeK jn\n1929. Average prices for stocks showed\na gain of 3 per cent over the preceding\nweek, but were lower when compared\nwith the same period a year ago. Rep\nresentative bond prices registered gains\nover both prior periods. Interest rates\nfor call money were slightly higher\nthan the preceding period, but showed\na marked decline from a year ago. In\nterest rates for time money showed de\ndines from both comparative periods.\nBusiness failures were reported to be\nfewer than during a week ago.\nThe activity of steel mills at the end\nof the week of June 28 showed a slight\ndecline from the week of June 21 and\nwas well below the level of a year ago.\nThe volume of building, as measured\nby the number of contracts awarded,\nduring the week ended June 28 showed\nconsiderable gains over both prior\nperiods.\nCheck payments, bank loans and dis\ncounts, and stock prices for the week\nended July 5, 1930, registered increases\nwhen compared with the week ended\nJuly 7, 1928.\n1 PESSIMISM THE SIGNAL\nFOR BUSINESS REVIVAL\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, July 12.\u2014One of the\ni encouraging signs pointing to the be\nginning of a business revival is the ex\ni treme pessimism that pervades the\nbusiness world at the present time, ac\ncording to the Alexander Hamilton In\ni stitute. In the past, business sentiment\nhas always been excessively pessimistic\ni prior to an upturn in business, just as\ni overoptimism has always preceded a\nslump. It will be recalled that busi\nness men were as optimistic last Sum\nmer as this Summer they are pessi\nmistic.\nBusiness indicators which have come\nto hand during the past week have not\nbeen unanimously unfavorable. Since\nthe beginning of June checks cashed\nt have shown a steady improvement, as\n1 compared with a year ago. The\nl changes from last year for each of the\npast four weeks were as follows: \u201418.4\nper cent, \u201410.2 per cent, \u20145.4 per cent\nr and +l.B per cent.\n1 Another encourajflpg feature has\nbeen -the Increase in''commercial loans.\npoint of capital, It Is necessary for deal\ners In small loans to charge anywhere\nfrom 14 to 34 P\u00abr cent a month, de\npending on the manner in which the\nloan is made.\nMore Loan Sources Needed.\n\"Investigations have also revealed the\ndisconcerting fact that these discount\ning companies and such banks as are\nwilling to do the expensive Individual\nloan business, are able to meet but a\npitifully small portion of the existing\nneed for emergency funds. Some au\nthorities think that more than half of\nthe people In our cities, when they run\nup against hospital bills, funeral ex\npenses, periods of unemployment or\nother emergencies which demand im\nmediate funds, are unable to secure\naccommodation from these agencies be\ncause evei\\ where as much as 18 per\ncent a year is being charged there is\nnot left to the lender a sufficient fund\nto enable him to cope with any loans\nexcept those which are not going to\ninvolve heavy expenses of collection.\n\u201cNaturally, It is this mass of unsatis\nfied borrowers which becomes the prey\nof the high-rate lenders against whom\nyou write, for in his dire need a man\ncan be made to agree to pay almost\nanything for the funds he cannot get\nalong without. Frequent contact with\nthis situation In connection with Its\ncharitable work led the Russell Sage\nFoundation of New York some years\nago to draw up the uniform small loan\nlaw, which has since been adopted in\n25 States. This law was designed to\nenable people who were unable to es\ntablish bank credit, offer collateral or\nendorsers to obtain money In time of\nneed at rates that were not unfair.\n\u201cSuch rates, the foundation learned\nafter much study of the situation, had\nto be considerably above those charged\nby banks on large, well secured com\nmercial loans. Banks, too. admit, as a\nrule, that they are not making a direct\nprofit on small loans made to indi\nviduals. Three and a half per cent a\nmonth was found to be essential to\nkeep enough capital in the field to sup\nply the demand for loans. That does\nnot mean that all lenders operating\nunder the law were expected to charge\n3 1'2 per cent, but that none was to\ncharge more than that. However, no\nfees were to be added, and interest\ncharges were not to be discounted in\nadvance, but to be charged from month\nto month and only on such funds as\nwere actually In the customer\u2019s hands\nCapital Needs New Law.\n\"It is our belief that Congress made\na grave mistake when it defeated the\nuniform small loan law for the Dis\ntrict of Columbia. Washington's people\ndo, as you say. face a real problem in\nthe illegal lender, who Is charging what\nthe traffic will bear.\n\u201cThe small loan business is full of\npitfalls and paradoxes\u2014there are com\nplex social and economic considerations\ninvolved, and It is natural that those\nwho have not given it deep study re\nact against the business. However, we\ndo ask you to believe that practically\nevery thinker who has taken the time\nto go into the subject rather carefully\nhas concluded that the Russell Sage\nFoundation uniform small loan law is\nthe most progressive and effective re\nmedial legislation yet devised to rectify\nan age-old problem.\u201d\nlcize a recent arti\ncle appearing In\nthis column, at\nlength and in a\nvery pleasant, civil\nmanner.\nPu b 1 Ration of\nthe criticism and\nthe info rmation\ngiven on the inside\nof the business was\ni not asked, but it is\nsuch a meaty let\nter that publica\ntion is gladly\ngiven, with the in\ntent of advancing\nthe viewpoint of\nthe Leanaer.\nName and ad\nCOMMODITIES NOW\nj HOLD SPOTLIGHT\nTen of Fifteen Groups Go\nLower During Week \u2014Three\nRecord Advances.\nBY H. N. McGILL,\nEditor of McGill Commodity Service.\nAUBURNDALE, MASS., July 12 (/P).\n\u2014Declining commodity prices again\nheld the spotlight as the feature event\nin business conditions. The average\nof all commodities reached another new\nlow. During the week Just closed, out\nof 15 individual groups, 10 declined, 2\nremained unchanged and 3 advanced.\nThe volume of business in early July\ndropped to a new low. surpassing the\nbreak during the closing months of\n1929 and early 1930. An outstanding\ndisturbing influence is the further de\ncline in the price line of agricultural\nproducts. There is an oversupply of\nfoods and feeds throughout the world.\nThe United States wheat crop promises\nJto exceed 800.000,000 bushels. Canadian\noutput should approach 400,000,000\nbushels, aggregating a total North\nAmerican supply of 1,200,000,000 bush\nels.\nAcreage for most farm products has\nbeen increased rather than cut down.\nThe outlook is for a com crop sharply\nabove a year ago. Prices of agricultural\nproducts are flucutuating violently en\ndeavoring to readjust themselves to a\nnew\u2019 crop basis.\nThere are no definite signs that the\ndownward tendency in all commodity\nprices in the industrial, live stock, agri\nthe past it is interesting to note that\neven after general business had reached\nits low and turned definitely upward,\ncommodity prices continue to gradually\nsag for a period of two to four months.\nDuring the past week all commodity\nprices did not decline with the rapidity\nnoted in June, yet a new low was es\ntablished, caused principally by lower\nprices in the industrial, livestock, argi\ncultural, non-ferrous metals, ferrous\nmetals and textile groups.\nPrices of industrial commodities re\ncorded only a minor decline. Higher\nquotations in building materials and\nfuels due to anthracite, and a further\nupturn in hides and leather counter\nacted the downward tendency in other\ngroups. For the first time since last\nOctober inventories of Industrial com\nmodities have started to decline.\nPrices of live stock have suffered more\nthan any other group during the past\nmonth. Since the third week in June\nthe price decline measures 12 per cent.\nFORMER LOCAL BANKER\nSAVINGS BANK CASHIER\nHarold J. Seeley of 21 Denwood ave\nnue, Takoma Park, has been appointed\nsecretary and treasurer of the Chen\nango Valley Savings Bank, Bingham\nton, N. Y\u201e effective August 1, 1930.\nFor the past four years Mr. Seeley\nhas been assistant national bank ex\naminer in New York State, previous to\nwhich he was employed as a note teller\nat the Federal-American National Bank\nof Washington, and graduated from\nWashington Chapter, American Insti\ntute of Banking.\nAfter a short vacation in this city, Mr.\nSeeley will leave to take up hia duties\nat Binghamton.\nCROP LOSSES HIGH\nAS STORMS SWEEP\nPARTS OF EUROPE\nReview Shows Industrial Out\nput and Business Are\nLittle Changed.\nGILT-EDGED SECURITIES\nPROVIDE BRIGHT SPOT\nDetails of New Automobile Tax in\nItaly of Vital Concern to\nUnited States.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, July 12.\u2014Cable dis\npatches to the Business Week give the\nfollowing survey of business abroad for\nthe week ending July 12:\nEurope.\u2014Business is dull. Industrial'\nproduction in general remains little\nchanged. Stock markets are stagnant,\nbut with gilt-edged securities providing\none bright spot. Heavy storms last\nveek were disastrous to crops, particu\nlarly in France, Germany, Switzerland\nand Greece. Otherwise doldrums pre\nvail.\nThe International Steel Cartel an\nnounced that complete accord has been\nconcluded by its members for the crea\ntion of selling bureaus for semi-finished\nproducts and for structural steels. The\nbureaus will centralize all orders and\ntransmit them to their respective na\ntional bureaus, already in existence in\nFrance and Germany, and soon to be\ncreated in all other adhering countries.\nOrders will be prorated according to the\nquota of each participant.\nUnity of interest is strengthening\nthe German-Britlsh-Belgian copper\nblock. Though a boycott of American\ncopper has been proposed, inside au\nthorities consider such a move imprac\ntical and anticipate only a strengthen\ning of the copper association to present\na united front.\nThe International Nitrogen Confer\nence, meeting in Paris, has settled im\nportant differences of view regarding\nproduction quota assignments, opening\nthe way for negotiations between the\nsynthetic makers of Europe and the\nnatural nitrate industry of Chile.\nBusiness Better in Britain.\nGreat Britain\u2014The general tone of\nbusiness is better, but commodity and\nstock activities are unimproved. The\nbankers\u2019 resolution favoring protection\nthrough tariffs is the dominating event\nof the business week and suggests a\nturning point in fiscal history, since it\nfollows a similar about-face by the\nManchester Chamber of Commerce.\nWith these strongholds of free trade\nnow in revolt, a general election may\nbe precipitated. Chief significance of\nthe bankers' resolution 1s the signature\nof Mr. McKenna, chairman of Eng\nland\u2019s largest commercial bank, ex-\nLlberal chancellor, and lifelong free\ntrader. This divides the city into two\ncamps\u2014the free trade group supported\nby Gov. Norman of the Bank of Eng\nland. and those favoring a protective\ntariff, now supported by the McKenna\ngroup.\nBarrow Haematite Steel Co. plans re\nconstruction involving new capital\ntotaling $1,000,000; United Steel Co.'s\nreconstruction will involve organization\nof a new company to be capitalized at\n$35,000,000. Imperial Chemicals have\ndenied rumors that they are in a shaky\ncash position. The suggestions got\nabroad when It was said that Lord Mel\nchett was raising $5,000,000 through\nthe Bank of England. Public confidence\nin this rationalized industry, however,\nhas been seriously shaken by the rumor. 1\nGermany\u2019s Tax Problem.\nGermany.\u2014lndefinite delay of con\ncerted action for the lowering of prices j\nand wages, improved chances tha' Dr\nDietrich's taxation program will secure\na parliamentary majority, thus giving\nGerman public finance a much needed\nbreathing space till late Autumn, and\nunabated business depression\u2014these\nare the features of the current business\nweek in Germany. The stock exchange\nis particularly depressed by rumors\nthat the two big shipping companies\u2014\nHapag and North German LloVd\u2014will\nbe forced to pass dividends for the cur\nrent year due to unsatisfactory earn\nings.\nThough these rumors are officially\ndenied and all surmises regarding divi\ndends are declared premature, it is gen\nerally known in all business circles that\nearnings of all shipping companies un\ndoubtedly are considerably below last\nyear's record, because of the upset con\nditions in the freight market. The\nbusiness failure of Schuchardt\nSchutte, leading German machine-tool\ndealers, wdth an extensive sales organi\nzation spread over Europe, which rep\nresents also 30 American machine and\nmachine-tool manufacturers, contrib\nutes to the general business pessimism.\nThe General Motors-owned Opel A.\nG. has issued an optimistic report\nboasting an increase in sales for the\nfirst six months of the current year of\n12 per cent compared with a decline in\ntotal German automobile sales in the\nsame period of 22 per cent.\nTrade Spotty in France.\nFrance.\u2014Business proceeds unevent\nfully, but is showing remarkable general\nresistance to adverse conditions which\nare now becoming more apparent be\ncause of the seasonal slowdown. Cer\ntain branches of production are begin\nning to suffer, as is evident in falling\nprices of numerous commodities, de\nclining foreign trade, increasing wages\nand narrowing profit margins, especial- i\nly in the iron and steel, automobile and\ntextile industries.\nIt is apparent now\u2019 that France,\nwhose economic activities were at a\nmaximum during 1929, the acutest\nperiod of the world crisis, will ex\nperience serious difficulties in readjust\nment when other countries are well on\nthe road to recovery. The industrial\npolicy which is striving to maintain\nthe present wage, price and production\nlevels, Ls considered harmful now, for\nit handicaps France in international\ncompetition at a time when foreign\ntrade has become increasingly vital to\nprosperity.\nFrench trade with the United States\nLs diminishing. Imports during the\nfirst five months were $199,000,000. a\ndrop of $13,000,000 from 1929. Exports\nfor the same period were $43,000,000, a\ndecline of $7,000,000. Meanwhile pur\nchases from Germany rose $34,000,000.\nItaly.\u2014Effective at once, a new sales\ntax of m per cent will be levied by\nthe Italian government on all sales, to\nprovide funds for national defense and\npublic works. There has been a general\nsales tax of V 2 per cent on sales of all\nproducts except foodstuffs.\nOs moat vital importance to Ameri\ncans are the details of the new auto\nmobile tax. To cover the new tariff,\nFord, Essex and Chevrolet, which for\nmerly sold for $1,500, will now cost\n$2,300. Nash, Hudson and Chrysler 75.\nwhich formerly sold at $2,300, now go to\n$3,800. ffcckard and Lincoln and other\negrs in that general class will be little\nClassified Ads\nPages 5 to 11\nNew Credit Head\nCHARLES W. CLAYTON\nIs the newly elected president of the\nWashington Association of Credit Men.\nsucceeding Lister T. Watts. He is an\nofficial of the F. P. May Hardware Co.,\nand has long been a leader in the as\nsociation\u2019s affairs. Harris Ewing.\n\u2022CHAIN STORE SALES\nDOWN 4 PER CENT\n25 Leading Systems in June\nHad Large Decrease in\nGross Turnover.\nGross sales of 25 of the leading chain\nstore systems for the month of June\nshowed a drop of approximately 4 per\ncent, compared with the same period\nlast year, whereas for the six months\nended with June sales for the same\nsystems showed an increase of approxi\nmately one-half of one per cent, com\npared with sales reported for the same j\nperiod of 1929. The drop in sales\nfor June, 1930, is in line with the\ngeneral trend of chain store sales ex\nperienced during recent months, but\nthe decline may be partly attributed\nto the fact there were only four Satur\ndays in June this year, compared with\nfive Saturday's in June, 1929. Lower\ncommodity prices also affected gross\nvolume of sales in some instances.\nSales $150,668,942.\nSales of the 25 chain store systems\naggregated $150,668,942 for June, 1930,\nagainst $156,956,141 reported for June,\n1929, a decrease of $6,287,199, or 4.0\nI per cent, according to a compilation of\nGeorge H. Burr Co. Os the respec\ntive systems losses in sales were re\nported by Sears Roebuck: Co., F. W.\nWoolworth, Kroger Grocery, S. S.\nKresge, National Tea Co., McCrory\nStores and National Bellas-Hess. Mont\ngomery Ward Co. and the majority\nof the smaller chains reported gains for\nthe month.\nFor the first half of the year 1930\nthe respective companies reported gross\nsales of $885,570,384, compared with\nsales of $881,032,978 reported for the\nI corresponding period last year, the in-\nI crease of $4,537,306 being equal to 0.51\nj per cent.\nJune Salea of Systems.\nSales of the individual store systems\nfor June and six months follows:\nJune. 1930. Increase.\nSears Roebuck $31,475,143 *52,533,246\nMontgomery Ward.... 23.989.300 2.035.661\nWoolworth 20.714.731 *2,896.031\nKroger 20.317.241 *1,582,116\nKresge 11.400.123 *1.171.672\nNational Tea 6.643,263 *897.602\nGrant 5.469,105 94.954\nS H. Gress 5.220,761 336,239\nI McCrory 3.211,795 *122.874\nBellas Hess 3.232.338 *1,018.328\nF. W 2.565.268 63,692\nI Schulte-United 2.164.460 691.421\ni Daniel Reeves 2.563.674 71.453\nI Lerner 2.156.577 469.830\ni McLellan 1.882.401 101.938 j\nPender 1.161.477 *49.402\ni Southern Stores 1.170.800 *2.300\nMetropolitan 1.337.460 *126.680\nNeisner 1.344.264 97.585\nSchiff Co 876.566 128.397\nBickford's. Inc 463.951 47.686\nEdison Bros 379.304 53.609\nKline Bros 382.687 *67.722\nFederal Bake 318.549 *22.787\nM. H. Fishman 189.904 11.146\n$150,668,942 *56,287,199\nHalf-year Sales.\nSears Roebuck $172,276,013 *35.911.480\nMontgomery Ward 130.185.103 \u20227.377<563\nWoolworth 131.318.974 *4.490.978\nKroger 132.451.942 *6.268.467\nKresge 67.457.612 176.846\nNational Tea 43.114.329 *1.900.715\nGrant 30.012,691 3.141.100\n8 H. Kress 30.314.684 1.542.035\nMcCrory Stores 19.410.320 384.586\nBellas-Hess 18.280.445 *7.087,220\nF. A- W 13.665.838 1.350.937\nSchulte-United 11.783.250 5.696.523\nDaniel Reeves 18.202.704 714.023\nLerner 11.297.263 3.389.151\nMcLellan 9.594.525 594.524\nPender 7,792.744 288.240\nSouthern 8.366.015 955.236\nMetropolitan 7.157.376 370.568\nNeisner 6.934.295 1,195.436\nSchiff 4.695.439 924,764\nBickford's 2.867.680 284.534\nEdison Bros 2.266.941 515.378\nKline Bros 2.039.188 45.899\nFederal Bake 2.259.649 65,132\nM. H. Fishmant 825,164 173.693\n$885,570,384 $4,537,306\n\u2022Decrease.\nAUTO FIRMS SOUND\nDURING SALES DROP\nFirst Half Year Finds Many Im\nportant Changes in Business\nMethods.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nDETROIT, July 12.\u2014Despite curtailed\nearnings due to the general business\nslump, the automobile manufacturers\nhave been able to preserve a solid fin\nancial front following completion of\nhalf a year in which operations have\nbeen subjected to a deflation process.\nThis applies to all but a bare hand\nful of plants whose small production\nand limited distribution have placed\nthem under severe handicap in a period\nlike the present. In only one instance\nhas a receivership been threatened, and\nin this case such action has been re- 1\nsisted. with operations continued.\nThe readjustment has brought with\nit elimination of excess overhead, re\nform of the used-car trade-, reduction of\nsurplus executive personnel and scrap-\nping of entire lines of cars that have\nproved unworthy from the standpoint\nof sales volume. It has also been\nmarked by improvement in dealer re\nlations which is likely to* rehabilitate\nthe retail end, long in need of rebuild\nin *L\u2014 i\ni\naffected because the former duty of\n35 per cent ad valorem plus specific\nbecomes entirely specific by weight.\nDuties on chassis correspond; on\nparts are even higher in proportion to 1\nprevent assembling of foreign cars in\nItaly. All American agencies yrill prob- 1\nably close except those in the expensive I\nclass, and Ford, whose cars will oe 1\nmanufactured through 4n arrangement J\nwith Isotta-Fraschini. h\nRAIL GIANTS SEEK\nTO EORCEMERGER\nOF WESTERN LINES\nGreat Northern Renews Old\nFight to Secure Entry\nInto California.\nUNION AND SOUTHERN\nPACIFIC ARE OPPOSED\nLatest Moves Considered Vital to\nVan Sweringens and Their\nExpansion Flans.\nT\nBY JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nBpeci\u00bbl Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, July 12.\u2014The hand of\nArthur Curtiss James of New York, th*\nlargest stockholder In the Great North-,\nem, as well as In the Western Pacific,\nis seen In the latest battle of the West\nern railroad giants. Ever since the days\nof James J. Hill the Great Northern\nhas locked forward to the time it would\nenter California. It has waited a long\ntime, but now its hopes are about to\nbe realized.\nWhen the Van Sweringens bought into\nthe Missouri Pacific, they hoped that\nthe Western Pacific could be secured to\ntie into their plans for a transconti\nnental line. But Mr. James and his\nassociates thought otherwise. So tha\ndecision, just announced by the Inter\nstate Commerce Commission, giving ap\nproval to the joint project of the Great\nNorthern and the Western Pacific for\nthe construction of a 200-mile Klamath\nFalls extension is of vast importance to\nCalifornia and the West.\nThis decision was announced over the\nbitter opposition of the Union Pacifiq\nand the Southern Pacific, particularly\nthe latter. So a new railroad giant U\nrising in the West to compete for West\nern business with these two transcon\ntinental roads.\nThe new program gives the Great\nNorthern its opportunity to get intq\nSan Francisco. That\u2019s the goal of Mr,\nJames, and has been for many years.\nThis new joint construction is not\nlarge factor In cost\u2014about $15,000,000-.\nbut it\u2019s the strategy that is important;\nFor the moment it sets back the Van\nSweringens in their ambitious program\nfor the Missouri Pacific. But it pushe*\nahead the James program and. ol\ncourse, vastly adds to the strength ol\nboth the Western Pacific and the Great\nNorthern as individual roads.\nMerger Bitterly Fought.\nWhat about the merger of the Great\nNorthern and the Northern Pacific!\nIt has been bitterly fought, not only\nby the Milwaukee railroad, but by\nscores of influential business men, citlei\nand towns, as well as financial lnstitu-\ntlons of the West. It is very doubtful\nif the merger will be approved, foi\nthe present.\nBut should be merger of the two intq\nthe Great Northern Pacific be approved\nby the Interstate Commerce Commis\u00ab\nsion it would, with this new Western\nPacific program, make that road ony\nof the giants of continental America.\nNearly every indication points thy\nother way; at least, so far as the merger\napproval is concerned. Nevertheless,\nthe Great Northern has had a distincf\nvictory in this latest ruling, one thal\nit doubtless will follow up and strengthen\n\u201cTom Thumb Golf\u201d Originator.\nGarnet Carter, hotel proprietor o|\nFairyland Inn, on Lookout Mountain\nTenn., is the originator of the \"Tow\nI Thumb golf\u201d courses which have swepj\ni the country with such a mighty fores\ni this Summer.\nA year ago Mr. Carter noticed hiy\nguests used the little inexpensive\ncourse that he installed In front o|\nthe hotel more than they did his regu\u00ab\nlar 18-hole course, which cost hiw\n$340,000. It started him thinking.\nWhen the District of Columbia Aske(\nhim to design a small course for oni\nof its parks, he patented his special\ngreens and named them the \"Tory\nThumb Golf\u201d course. Today th|\nCarter course consists of 18 holes, frory\n26 to 50 feet long, which Include trap*\npassageways, bunkers\u2014plenty of haz.\nards. The putter only is used.\nToday there are more than 5.001\n\u201cTom Thumb\" courses, paying royaltlej\nto Mr. Carter. The small towns are tak\u00ab\ning to them even more rapidly thay\nthe big cities, because of their lnabilitj\nto have large golf courses.\nMore Wheat Predicted.\nThe United States Government\u2019s wheal\ncrop estimate of 807,265,000 bushel)\nfor 1930 is a slight increase over lasj\nyear.\nWhile the Spring wheat area In.\ncreased 3.3 per cent over 1929, witl\n16,163,000 acres planted this year, li\nrepresents an increase of 7.5 per cenl\nabove the five-year average.\nBut in the Winter wheat, farmers cu|\ntheir acreage so that the total wheal\nacreage of all kinds shows a reductloy\nof ,4.1 per cent. The total acreage plant,\ned this year was 38,490,000 acres, com.\npared with the 5-year average area ol\n35,585,000 acres.\nThe problem of wheat storage is be.\ncoming a major one. Reports persist\nthat thousands of railroad cars an\nnow loaded with the new Winter wheal\ncrop, waiting for a fair price.\nEurope's restricted buying at the mo.\nment is not helping the situation. Bu:\nthe wheat farmer is not the only oni\nsuffering from low prices. Cattle toda;\nare selling at about $4 a hundred\npounds less than they were a year ago\nEvery cattleman who bought six month)\nago to feed has lost money. This ii\nalso true of those who bought sheep.\n\u2022So the wheat grower, had he turney\nto sheep or cattle this year, wouli\nhave had no better prospects than h|\nnow faces.\nExport Fruit Company Formed.\nA Chile company, amply financed, ]i\nbeing formed to export vast quantitiej\nof Chilean fruit to the United States\nApples, melons, grapes, plums ant\npeaches, pears, as well as a variety oy\ntropical fruits, are the fruits the ue\u00bb\ncompany expects to sell in the Unitaff\nStates. The first shipment of appi*\nproduced in Central Chile has arrived\nand the exhibits are \u201cdandies.\u201d\nHoneydew melons from Chile wen\nsold In New York in January. Thou,\nsands of crates of' Chilean peaches wen\nsold last Winter in New York.\nA. F. dl Valvasone, director of thy\nChilean Information Bureau, sees a bli\nfuture In this field for Chile. Durini\n1929. the United States imported 9 00|\ncubic feet of grapes, 3,690,000 pound!\nof melons, 32,000 pounds of pluma\n5,000 pounds of peaches and 4,001\npounds of pears.\nThe United Fruit Co. has for yean\nbeen importing South American fruity\nInto the United States, bananas par.\nticularly. But little of the Chile&y\nfisilt has been sold in the United States,**\n(Ooprrltht. mo.)","height":"24993","width":"19389"}}
